title: For Sale:  Bond Arms Snake Slayer IV
postcontent:
I am selling my Bond Arms Snake Slayer IV, as well as extra grips and a soft pocket holster. This model has 4 ¼” barrels chambered in .45 Colt / .410 (both 3” and 2 ½”). 

As the first two images show, the barrels have some light surface scratching, so the exterior is at only perhaps 95%. The workings have been very well cared for: it has fired fewer than one hundred rounds, and has been dry-fired only twice (neither time by me). 

I purchased this derringer in order to explore some ideas for non-standard .410 shot. The tests were at standard pressure, but the projectiles slightly damaged the rifling of both barrels, as the third image shows. This damage does not at all affect the gun’s performance: these barrels are great for .410, but the short, shallow rifling at the muzzle (as well as the long freebore behind it) does not treat .45 Colt very well—and never did, right from the beginning. Bond Arms does sell barrels that are fully rifled and that chamber either .45 Colt or .45 ACP—4 ¼” by special order, 3 ½” from their website. Like all of their barrels, these will fit this frame. In good conscience, I can only recommend shotshells in any .45/.410 barrels, and this model shoots them very well (the extra barrel length both increases the velocity and decreases the felt recoil, so the Federal .410 handgun loads are quite adequate for self-defense).

The Snake Slayer IV is rarely in stock anywhere around here, so with shipping, sales tax and transfer fees, this gun with the extra grips cost me more than $650 earlier this year—and other than the cosmetic damage to the rifling, it is like new. $500 is a reasonable price and we need the money—I’ll throw in most of a box of 3” birdshot and half a box of 2 ½” Federal buckshot. Also, I’m willing to trade up and pay the difference, but the only gun I’m looking for is a Super Redhawk in .454.

title: For Sale:  Rare Robinson M96
postcontent:
Here is a hard to find Robinson Armament M96 (I bought New) which is a semi-automatic version of the Stoner automatic rifle that was in competition with the M16 in the Vietnam Era. Many believe this design was much better than the M16 yet it still did not prevail for political reasons. Here is a chance to own a very well made semi automatic rifle and a piece of history as well so don't miss out.

Robinson Armament M96 Expeditionary Rifle in pristine condition. I would rate 99%. Fired very little, less than 400 rounds. Has original rear sight. Original non-modified trigger. Very nice, clean trigger pull. Smoothest shooting .223 semi auto that I have fired, excellent ergonomics. Guns has always functioned with no issues. 

USES AR-15 Magazines!



M96 Expeditionary Rifle

Review

The Robinson Armament M96 Expeditionary rifle broke onto the scene in late 1999 as the first new American designed "assault rifle" to be brought into production in many years. Tracing its heritage back to the Stoner M63, and sharing design traits with the AK, AR, and SIG 550 the M96 represents an interesting representation of various designs, in one well conceived package.

Although its heritage can be traced back to the the original Stoner 63, the only part that is common is the buttstock. The M96 utilizes a rotating multi-lug bolt (similar to an AR15 bolt), and a gas piston surrounded by a recoil spring, connected to the bolt to cycle the rifle (unlike the AR15, which uses direct gas pressure on the bolt carrier). The barrel assembly is a quick change design manufactured from 4140 steel that is 20" in length with an integrated muzzle compensator, and a 1 in 9 twist rate. A two stage trigger is featured as standard, as well as 100 and 500 yard adjustable sights. The receiver is manufactured from Stainless Steel, utilzing a welded construction of the frame, upper handguard, and barrel mounting point. All of these features weigh in at 7.6 lbs in a 40" package. 

Inspection of the M96 out of the box yielded a very tight and well built rifle. The takedown pins were tight, and unfortunately as they come from the factory, I find the protrusion from the right side of the receiver to be annoying - a simple workaround for this was to turn the pins around and feed them in from the right side of the receiver; much as the rear integrated takedown pin came from the factory - which minimized the extent to which those pins protrude. Doing the pin swap helped another problem, that of ergonomics and the magazine release - as the pin sits, it is terribly close to the magazine release and I found myself inadvertantly trying to press it more than once. Sights are adjustable for elevation and windage at the front and rear sights, unfortunately the front sight windage adjustment requires the use of a hex head key, which is not included with the rifle. On the positive side the safety is large, and allows for quick transitions from Safe to Fire. Ergonomics are good, with the rifle feeling a little muzzle heavy when compared to an AR15.


Initial firing of 200 rounds at the range was flawless. I utilized 55gr Winchester Ball and a variety of US military contractor magazines and one Thermold magazine. As suggested in the manual, I started firing with the gas port completely closed, but opened it up after a few rounds to half way through the settings to allow for the brass to be ejected approximately 7-10ft. The only problem at the end of the days firing was a loosening of the grip assembly, which was easily remedied (this was also exhibited on a second test gun that I fired). Much like the SIG 550 and FAL, the M96 bounces fired brass off the portion of receiver directly behind the ejection port; a series of small brass marks was visible at the end of the days firing. Felt recoil was less than that of a Colt SP1 that I fired for comparison, and was similar to a SIG 550. This reduced felt recoil can be attributed to an increased mass in the recripocating parts of the bolt and gas rod assembly, which helps reduce the amount of recoil energy that makes it to the shooters shoulder by disipating it to cycle the firearm.

Firing methodology consisted of firing 1 round every 5 seconds at a target 50 yards away; function firing was the primary concern, so not much concern was paid to accuracy. The group of 200 rounds did end up being about 1" wide by 3" tall; I attribute the vertical stringing to myself. Other shooters on the internet have noted accuracy with factory 55gr ammo in the range of 1.5" at 100yds.

Overall impressions of this rifle are good. The proximity of the magazine well takedown pin to the magazine release did cause some problems with fumbling to release the mag, and the grip loosening is not something that is uncommon with a new firearm. Reliability was exceptional for a brand new semi automatic rifle, and the ergonomics are good. With the planned introduction of a carbine version, a bren style feeding mechanism for the beginning of 2000, and a beltfed conversion further down the road, the future of this weapon system looks bright - I would not hesitate in purchasing another one.

title: For Sale:  COLT - U.S. CAVALRY REVOLVER -- SAA .45 Colt, Made 1882, Matching w/ Kopec Letter
location: New York, New York, United States
postcontent: Here's a significant piece of U.S. Military history and a wonderful piece of Americana. This is a Colt Single Action Army "U.S. Cavalry" revolver that was manufactured in 1882 for the United States military. This is a later "DFC" inspected gun with matching serial numbers. The barrel still measures the original 7-1/2" in length and was never modified to "Artillery" length as so many were. Overall condition is good but little original finish remains. The revolver is mostly a silver/brown with some scattered areas of light pitting. The "U.S." marking and patent dates on the frame are all crisply marked as is the proper rollmarking along the top of the barrel. The grips are sound and original. They are "D.F.C." and "P" marked on the base and have the proper "JEG" (Capt. John E. Greer) cartouche which would be appropriate for guns in the 81,900 to 111,700 serial range. The mechanics are in good working order and the revolver functions well with some minor looseness. The bore rates about good to very good with strong rifling and only a few areas of pitting. The accompanying Kopec letter notes that some screws may be later replacements and the ejector spring is not original. The letter incorrectly states that the grips are non-original but closer examination has proved this not to be the case and they are correct for the gun. Probably the most iconic revolver associated with the Old West, the U.S. marked Single Action Army, particularly the Cavalry Model, is a highly prized collector's piece. An original gun, matching gun in any condition is a difficult item to locate. With the uncertain political climate and economic set-backs, this might be a good way to tuck away a little money for a rainier day. Buyer pays $30.00 shipping. This is an antique revolver and as such, no FFL is required in most areas and it can be shipped directly to the lucky buyer.

title: For Sale:  Earliest known Winchester 20ga. w/Madis letter
location: New York, New York, United States
postcontent: It seems that when it comes to Winchester collecting, it is difficult to find a piece that is TRULY unique. This is that kind of collectible firearm.  I am looking forard to this gun having more exposure than it would otherwise get in a private auction. In 1878, with its name firmly established in the rifle trade, Winchester decided that it was time to get into the shotgun market. With no in-house facilities to produce shotguns, Winchester contracted with English gunmakers to produce the very first shotguns to carry the Winchester name. Less than 1500 of these English doubles were produced. Of this number, only 3 guns are known to exist with gauges other than 12 or 10; one is a 16 gauge and two are 20 gauges. Prior to its discovery by the current owner, it was thought that Match Gun #1314 was the oldest/only English 20ga. double to exist. In his book, "Winchester Shotguns and Shotshells," author Ronald Stadt features pictures of #1314, but specifically mentions #1312 at least three times. In the book, Stadt openly questions the existence of #1312 and perhaps what it was. 1312 is the oldest 20ga. shotgun to carry the company name. This shotgun is featured on p.7 of Dennis Adler's book, Winchester Shotguns. Full historical documentation in the form of a five-page handwritten letter from the late George Madis, foremost authority on Winchester firearms and author of "The Winchester Book," "The Winchester Model 12," and other definitive books, will be provided on the website dedicated to this gun. (see link) 1312's condition leaves quite a bit to be desired. It appears that someone attempted to refinish the stock. The wood as well as the checkering has been sanded and a coat of finish was applied. The original hammers have been replaced with others of the correct size. Thankfully, the metal was left untouched. There is pitting in the bores. Obviously the gun must never be fired, even with the proper ammunition. At this price, 1312 might be a good candidate for a restoration. This is a once in a lifetime chance for the collector to acquire a piece that is not only rare but historically significant. This gun has been in calendars and newspaper articles. This gun has allowed me to meet or correspond with authors and Winchester professionals that I would probably never have had the opportunity to meet. It's really been a lot of fun. A couple of years ago, I sent 1312 to Doug Turnbull Restorations for an examination. During a phone conversation, the restoration specialist told me that he was standing in a room full of some of the rarest Winchesters in existence, but 1312 was the only one that felt truly unique. He said that the others felt like variations of the same thing.  If you have any questions, feel free to email me. I will allow a five day inspection period with buyer paying all shipping charges. Item is guaranteed to be true to description on link page. Click on link for in depth description. "I've changed my mind" is not grounds for a refund. No FFL necessary for this auction. I reserve the right to end this auction at any time. Also, If you are interested in this gun, be sure and email me.

title: For Sale:  ANTIQUE   GUN   RESTORATION
postcontent:
Almost every family has great grandpa's old shotgun. It may have been in the family for generations! It is a keepsake but needs to be put into better shape. Parts may be missing or it won’t work. It may be rusty and the wooden parts deteriorated. You may simply want the old thing professionally cleaned -OR- Refurbished to a presentable state – OR - you may want it put into LIKE NEW shape! Perhaps you wish to present this family treasure, fully restored, for Christmas? Don't wait. It may take us DAYS to complete your project - once we get yours in line. 
We have a huge inventory or antique and hard-to-find parts along with hundreds of stocks and forearms. If we don’t have the antique part we may have to order it or – even MAKE it. As an example, most of the guns we restore are over 100 years old! For the time being at least, pre-1899 guns are completely EXEMPT from all federal laws. 
We can offer Professional Results. Your family heirloom will look, "Good as great Grandpa bought it!"
We are not a dealer and do not sell guns. However, we can restore your family treasure to its original out-of-the box appearance. Each project is priced based upon the level of complexity at the customer's request and the current condition of the piece. Most of our projects are old shotguns and rifles.

title: For Sale:  Custom Built Mauser Action. .30-06 Ackley Improved
location: Missoula Bozeman Butte Helena, Montana, United States
postcontent:
This was my dad's rifle custom built by his Gunsmith at Capital Sports in Helena in the 90s. I don't know everything about it but this is what I know.
Ackley Improved chambers blow out the shoulder of the case to decrease body taper and increase shoulder angle, resulting in a higher case capacity. This will make a .30-06 shoot like a .300 Win. Mag. It is built on a Mauser Action which has had the "cock on open" conversion done and the rear sight milled off and tapped for a 1 piece base. It is fitted with a medium/heavy Military Barrel that was brand new for a .30 cal machine gun on an army tank. It started at 30" but has been cut down to 22" and reblued. I'm not sure what trigger was used but it feels light and crisp. It has a Leupold M8 6X which is a fixed 6 power. The stock has been bedded and is a nice piece of wood but does have some dings from over the years.
This gun has only had a couple of boxes of shells through it since it was built. It is a sub MOA gun with good 168 gr. ammo. My dad's knees were bad and he never really got to hunt with it. He didn't even blow out enough cases to ever reload for it.

All and all this is a great rifle at a great price just in time for hunting season! $550.00 or best offer
